# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

## Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. It was removed because it caused corrupted state — aborting mid-lock, mid-write, etc.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also removed** — no longer needed since abort can't happen.
3. **`ThreadAbortException` will never be thrown** by the runtime.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _cts.Cancel();

        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
            var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
            if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
            {
                // Log warning: worker did not stop within timeout.
                // There is NO safe forced-kill equivalent in .NET 8.
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking `GetNextItem()`** | If it blocks without checking a token, cancellation hangs forever. You *must* make it accept a `CancellationToken` (e.g., use `Channel<T>.ReadAsync(token)` or `BlockingCollection.Take(token)`). |
| **No forced kill exists** | .NET 8 has no safe `Abort()` replacement. Design all work to be cooperatively cancellable. If you wrap unmanaged/third-party code that can't be cancelled, isolate it in a **separate process** and kill that process. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | A `volatile` flag can't unblock a thread stuck in `Thread.Sleep`, I/O, or `WaitHandle.WaitOne`. `CancellationToken` integrates with all of these via `.WaitHandle` and async APIs. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` in Stop()** | Replace with `await Task.WhenAny(task, Task.Delay(...))` — non-blocking, precise, and testable. |
| **Fire-and-forget Task.Run** | Always store the returned `Task` and observe it on shutdown. Unobserved exceptions silently disappear otherwise. |

## If You Can't Go Fully Async

Use `CancellationToken` with synchronous blocking APIs:

```csharp
// Instead of Thread.Abort to break out of a blocking call:
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // BlockingCollection natively supports cancellation
        var item = _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
        ProcessItem(item);
    }
}
```

**Bottom line:** Replace the abort-based "pull the plug" pattern with cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken` threaded through every blocking call. There is no shortcut — if any call ignores the token, graceful shutdown breaks.
